201
00:11:36,180 --> 00:11:38,253
It's establishing controls.

202
00:11:41,670 --> 00:11:46,670
So the three types of
governance controls, preventive.

203
00:11:47,340 --> 00:11:51,840
And here, we're simply making
sure that users and roles

204
00:11:51,840 --> 00:11:56,790
are restricted from performing
actions on resources.

205
00:11:56,790 --> 00:12:00,393
And this applies across
the CLI and console.

206
00:12:01,230 --> 00:12:03,423
And then with proactive controls,

207
00:12:04,440 --> 00:12:07,380
we're scanning the resources
before they're provisioned.

208
00:12:07,380 --> 00:12:10,530
And this can take place
with infrastructures code

209
00:12:10,530 --> 00:12:13,770
and sometimes developer pipelines.

210
00:12:13,770 --> 00:12:16,890
The benefit of proactive
controls is that this leads

211
00:12:16,890 --> 00:12:21,240
to developer development
efficiency along the same lines

212
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:24,810
of shifting left principles,
but we're catching the errors

213
00:12:24,810 --> 00:12:29,370
before it gets provisioned or deployed.

214
00:12:29,370 --> 00:12:31,770
And then the last advantage
of proactive controls too

215
00:12:31,770 --> 00:12:34,563
is also about the cost efficiency.

216
00:12:37,080 --> 00:12:39,330
We're preventing the
resources from being deployed,

217
00:12:39,330 --> 00:12:42,390
so that results in lower costs.

218
00:12:42,390 --> 00:12:44,390
Then the last one is detective controls.

219
00:12:45,270 --> 00:12:49,260
These are simply non-blocking
rules, but we'll tell you,

220
00:12:49,260 --> 00:12:51,030
we'll evaluate certain resources

221
00:12:51,030 --> 00:12:53,793
and tell you what's
compliant or non-compliant.

222
00:12:55,560 --> 00:13:00,560
So AWS organizations has
three preventive controls.

223
00:13:01,200 --> 00:13:03,870
Two of them launched last year,

224
00:13:03,870 --> 00:13:07,830
resource control policies
and declarative policies.

225
00:13:07,830 --> 00:13:09,720
With service control policies,

226
00:13:09,720 --> 00:13:12,840
we are preventing or
restricting identities

227
00:13:12,840 --> 00:13:15,330
based on API actions.

228
00:13:15,330 --> 00:13:18,663
And I'm sure everyone's
quite familiar with them,

229
00:13:19,710 --> 00:13:21,270
they've been around for several years,

230
00:13:21,270 --> 00:13:26,130
but you can apply them to
all of our AWS resources,

231
00:13:26,130 --> 00:13:29,100
containers, EC2, SageMaker and so on.

232
00:13:29,100 --> 00:13:33,990
Now, RCPs, resource control policies,

233
00:13:33,990 --> 00:13:38,760
define the maximum available
permissions on a resource.

234
00:13:38,760 --> 00:13:40,710
So we typically see this being used

235
00:13:40,710 --> 00:13:43,200
for data perimeter use cases,

236
00:13:43,200 --> 00:13:48,200
and it's very helpful
when we are able to apply

237
00:13:49,800 --> 00:13:54,800
what permissions can be
enabled on a service at scale

238
00:13:55,020 --> 00:13:57,810
across a multi account organization.

239
00:13:57,810 --> 00:14:01,167
And so the services that
it supports today are S3,

240
00:14:01,167 --> 00:14:02,703
KMS and Secrets Manager.

241
00:14:04,860 --> 00:14:07,470
But very powerful when
you don't have to think

242
00:14:07,470 --> 00:14:09,990
about what permissions should be allotted

243
00:14:09,990 --> 00:14:13,113
